# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Units
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oak:unit-3817
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Thematic Studies"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about a theme in British history over a period of roughly 1000 years. They examine this theme, analysing the impact it had in Medieval, Early Modern, Industrial and Modern Britain, with a particular focus on change and continuity."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on various units that deal with change and continuity from key stages 1, 2 and 3. It develops and reinforces pupils' big picture of the past that they have established in thematic units about seafarers and women. It also enriches and consolidates the majority of the units they studied at key stage 3, which focused on the medieval, early modern and modern worlds. This unit prepares pupils for the historic environment, where their thematic knowledge is consolidated and enriched by looking at a single place at a particular time in great detail.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """An working knowledge of some of the major political, religious, social and economic developments that have taken place in Britain over the last c1000 years
Familiarity with the second order concepts of change and continuity
Familiarity with the second order concepts of cause and consequence""" ;
  curric:id "3817"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.322829Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-history-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-invasion-migration-and-settlement .

oak:unit-786
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Historic Environment: Norman England"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the historical environment, choosing the relevant site study to complement their understanding of Norman England."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of Norman England, and any other units where they have studied a historic environment. This unit prepares pupils for any further study of the historic environment.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils arrive at their study of the historical environment with broad contextual knowledge of Norman England.
Pupils understand that England was a Christian country in the 11th century.
Pupils understand the nature of monarchy in the medieval period.
Pupils have a general understanding of the different roles people occupied in the medieval Church.
Pupils have an understanding of the significance of castles and other fortified places.""" ;
  curric:id "786"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.324969Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-history-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-invasion-migration-and-settlement .

oak:unit-3820
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Thematic studies"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about either migrants in Britain or medicine in Britain over a period of roughly 1000 years. They examine one of these themes, analysing the impact it had in Medieval, Early Modern, Industrial and Modern Britain, with a particular focus on change and continuity."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on various units that deal with change and continuity from key stages 1, 2 and 3. It develops and reinforces pupils' big picture of the past that they have established in thematic units about seafarers and women. It also enriches and consolidates the majority of the units they studied at key stage 3, which focused on the medieval, early modern and modern worlds. This unit prepares pupils for the historic environment, where their thematic knowledge is consolidated and enriched by looking at a single place at a particular time in great detail.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """A working knowledge of some of the major political, religious, social and economic developments that have taken place in Britain over the last c1000 years
Familiarity with the second order concepts of change and continuity
Familiarity with the second order concepts of cause and consequence""" ;
  curric:id "3820"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.325724Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-history-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-invasion-migration-and-settlement .

oak:unit-3828
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "British depth study: Anglo-Saxon and Norman England, c1060–88"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils study an aspect of British medieval history in depth. They learn about the social, economic, religious and political events that influenced the lives of those who lived in this period."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of England and Britain from the Stone Age to the early modern period that they built in key stages 2 and 3. This unit prepares pupils for the units they study in year 11, where some of the same themes relating to power, governance and religion are touched on again in both the period study and the modern depth study.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """An overview knowledge of England between the 8th and 11th centuries, with a focus on the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms, Viking invasion and settlement, and the creation of Anglo-Saxon England.""" ;
  curric:id "3828"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.331985Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-history-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-invasion-migration-and-settlement .

oak:unit-3822
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Historic environments"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils study a specific historical environment. They learn about the local context of this area and the way in which it interacted with national issues and the themes they have studied in their thematic study."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on the previous key stage 4 unit where pupils learnt about a theme through British history and the experiences of those touched by that theme. This unit prepares pupils for any further study of Britain in periods in which these historical environments are set, or of any other historical environments.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """A strong working knowledge of the relevant thematic study with which this unit is paired""" ;
  curric:id "3822"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.334109Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-history-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-invasion-migration-and-settlement .

oak:unit-3824
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Modern depth studies"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils study a modern society and the issues that affected it in great depth over a shorter period. They learn about the key events, developments, people and stories that shaped this modern society over a period of around twenty to thirty years."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Having examined various societies and civilisations in breadth and depth across all key stages, pupils now turn to the study of a society that they have not yet encountered, with a particular focus on how social, economic, cultural and political developments interacted in their chosen society. After deepening their knowledge of one modern society, pupils are prepared to contrast this with the society in which they live today, or any modern socities they might encounter in future study.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """A working knowledge of the broad local, national and international developments that occurred in the centuries preceding the period being studied.""" ;
  curric:id "3824"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.334908Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-history-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-power-government-and-religion ,
    oak:thread-empire-persecution-and-resistance .

oak:unit-3819
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Wider Depth Study - Conflict and tension between East and West, 1945–1972"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils undergo a wider depth study which tells a story about a period that shaped the world we live in today: the Cold War. They look at the key events, developments, people and stories that defined the international relations in this Cold War period."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on all of the historical knowledge that pupils have built across key stages 1 to 4 up to this point. It makes particular use of any units in which pupils constructed or deconstructed historical narratives. This unit prepares pupils for any further study of the modern international order or current affairs.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """A thorough grounding in substantive concepts commonly found across key stages 1, 2 and 3. For example, 'communism', 'ideology, 'international relations', 'conflict' and 'tension'.'.""" ;
  curric:id "3819"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.338481Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-history-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-warfare-and-conflict .

oak:unit-3823
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Period study: Superpower relations and the Cold War, 1941–91"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils undergo a period study which tells a story about a period that shaped the world we live in today: the Cold War. They look at the key events, developments, people and stories that defined the relationship between the USA and the USSR in this period."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on all of the historical knowledge that pupils have built across key stages 1 to 4 up to this point. It makes particular use of any units in which pupils constructed or deconstructed historical narratives. This unit prepares pupils for their final key stage 4 unit where their knowledge of broad period events is complemented by a specific depth study.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """A thorough grounding in substantive concepts commonly found across key stages 1, 2 and 3. For example, 'communism', 'ideology, 'international relations', 'conflict' and 'tension'.'.""" ;
  curric:id "3823"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.345554Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-history-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-warfare-and-conflict .

oak:unit-3816
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "British Depth Study: Norman England, c1066–c1100"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils study an aspect of British medieval history in depth. They learn about the social, economic, religious and political events that influenced the lives of those who lived in this period."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of England and Britain from the Stone Age to the early modern period that they built in key stages 2 and 3. This unit prepares pupils for the units they study in year 11, where some of the same themes relating to power, governance and religion are touched on again in both the period study and the modern depth study.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """An overview knowledge of England between the 8th and 11th centuries, with a focus on the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms, Viking invasion and settlement, and the creation of Anglo-Saxon England.""" ;
  curric:id "3816"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.351678Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-history-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-invasion-migration-and-settlement .

oak:unit-3818
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Period Studies"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils undergo a period study that provides an unfolding narrative which tells a story about a period that shaped the world we live in today. They look at the key events, developments, people and stories that defined the chosen period."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on all of the historical knowledge that pupils have built across key stages 1 to 4 up to this point. It makes particular use of any units in which pupils constructed or deconstructed historical narratives. This unit prepares pupils for their final key stage 4 unit where their knowledge of broad period events is complemented by a specific depth study.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """A thorough grounding in substantive concepts commonly found across key stages 1, 2 and 3. For example, 'monarchy', 'empire', 'international relations', 'conflict' and 'faith'.""" ;
  curric:id "3818"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.379578Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-history-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-power-government-and-religion ,
    oak:thread-empire-persecution-and-resistance .

